# Cafe Business Logic II - README

## Overview

This project demonstrates Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) concepts in Java by creating custom classes for products and customer orders. The application simulates a simple coffee shop ordering system where customers can place orders, add products, check order status, calculate totals, and display order details.

---

## Objectives

* Practice creating custom classes.
* Implement constructors and overloaded constructors.
* Use private member variables.
* Implement getters and setters.
* Work with ArrayLists.
* Create and use object methods.
* Apply Object-Oriented Programming principles.

---

## Project Structure

```text
src/
└── com.cafe
    ├── Product.java
    ├── CustomerOrder.java
    └── CoffeeShopTest.java
```

---

## Classes

### Product.java

Represents a menu item in the coffee shop.

#### Attributes

* name (String)
* price (double)

#### Methods

* Constructor
* Getters
* Setters

---

### CustomerOrder.java

Represents a customer order.

#### Attributes

* name (String)
* ready (boolean)
* products (ArrayList<Product>)

#### Methods

##### Constructors

* CustomerOrder()
* CustomerOrder(String name)

##### Business Logic Methods

* addItem(Product product)
* getStatusMessage()
* getOrderTotal()
* display()

##### Accessor & Mutator Methods

* getName()
* setName()
* isReady()
* setReady()
* getProducts()
* setProducts()

---

### CoffeeShopTest.java

Used to test all application functionality.

#### Test Cases

* Create products.
* Create two guest orders.
* Create three named orders.
* Add products to orders.
* Mark some orders as ready.
* Test status messages.
* Test order total calculations.
* Display all order details.

---

## Features Implemented

### Add Products

Products can be added to an order using:

```java
order1.addItem(coffee);
```

### Order Status Messages

Ready Order:

```text
Your order is ready.
```

Not Ready Order:

```text
Thank you for waiting. Your order will be ready soon.
```

### Calculate Order Total

Example:

```java
System.out.println(order1.getOrderTotal());
```

### Display Order Information

Example Output:

```text
Customer Name: Murad
Drip Coffee - $1.5
Cappuccino - $3.5
Total: $5.0
```

